<h2>What Is Work Anxiety?</h2>
<p>Work anxiety is a cluster of anxiety symptoms specifically tied to the workplace and professional identity. It's not a single diagnosis but encompasses several overlapping presentations:</p>
<ul>
  <li>Performance anxiety — fear of being evaluated, presenting, or being judged on work quality</li>
  <li>Anticipatory anxiety — dread before meetings, conversations with supervisors, deadlines</li>
  <li>Social anxiety at work — fear of colleagues, office dynamics, being scrutinised</li>
  <li>Perfectionism-driven anxiety — chronic fear that work is never good enough</li>
  <li>Fear of job loss, demotion, or professional failure</li>
  <li>Toxic workplace responses — anxiety and hypervigilance developed in response to genuinely difficult work environments</li>
</ul>

<h2>The Scale of the Problem</h2>
<p>Work-related stress and anxiety are among the leading drivers of mental health treatment-seeking. The American Institute of Stress finds that workplace stress is a major problem for 83% of US workers. Work anxiety predicts absenteeism, presenteeism (being at work but not functioning), turnover, and long-term burnout.</p>

<h2>When Anxiety Is About the Workplace vs. When It's About the Person</h2>
<p>This distinction matters for treatment. Some work anxiety is a reasonable response to an objectively problematic environment — a bullying manager, an unsustainable workload, job insecurity. Therapy in this context involves acknowledging the reality and helping someone respond effectively, rather than treating a legitimate response to a bad situation as a personal defect.</p>

<p>Other work anxiety involves cognitive and emotional patterns that generate anxiety regardless of the actual workplace — performance anxiety, perfectionism, fear of evaluation — where the internal patterns are the primary target.</p>

<h2>What Therapy Addresses</h2>

<h3>Cognitive Patterns</h3>
<p>Work anxiety typically involves specific distortions: overestimation of the probability of bad outcomes ("I'll definitely fail this presentation"), overestimation of the consequences ("If I fail I'll lose my job and my career will be over"), and underestimation of one's ability to cope. CBT identifies and tests these patterns through cognitive restructuring and behavioural experiments.</p>

<h3>Avoidance</h3>
<p>Anxiety drives avoidance — of presentations, of difficult conversations, of challenging assignments. Avoidance reduces anxiety short-term but maintains it long-term by preventing the disconfirming experiences that would reduce fear. Therapy involves graduated exposure to avoided work situations.</p>

<h3>Performance Anxiety and Evaluation Fear</h3>
<p>Fear of evaluation is a form of social anxiety applied to professional contexts. Treatment uses the same approach as social anxiety more broadly — testing the fear predictions, exposure to evaluation, and addressing the self-focused attention that amplifies anxiety during performance.</p>

<h3>Values and Meaning</h3>
<p>Sometimes work anxiety is a signal that the current role, organisation, or career path is misaligned with values. ACT-based work explores this angle — not as a quick escape from anxiety but as genuine inquiry into what matters and whether current choices reflect it.</p>

<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

<p><strong>My anxiety is caused by my job. Should I just leave?</strong><br/>
Maybe — but not necessarily. If the environment is genuinely toxic, leaving may be right. But anxiety often travels with us — a new job with the same untreated patterns produces the same anxiety. Therapy helps distinguish what's situational from what's internal.</p>

<p><strong>I can function at work — does that mean I don't have real work anxiety?</strong><br/>
Functioning despite anxiety doesn't mean the anxiety isn't significant. Many people perform at high levels while experiencing chronic anxiety privately. The cost in suffering and in the risk of eventual burnout is real.</p>

<p><strong>Will my employer find out I'm in therapy?</strong><br/>
No. Therapy is entirely confidential. No information is shared with employers. EAP (Employee Assistance Programme) counselling may involve limited reporting to employers — private therapy through a platform like Shemesh Wellness does not.</p>

